	<subsection>
		<title>Scalar Multiplication of Vectors</title>
		<p>
			In the <xref ref="sect-vectors-as-solutions" />, we saw the scalar multiplication of a vector.
			In <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>,
			this means
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				r \begin{bmatrix}
				x_1 \\ x_2
				\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
				r x_1 \\ r x_2
				\end{bmatrix}
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			in that each component of the vector is multiplied by the scalar <m>r</m>.
			Geometrically,
			multiplication by the scalar <m>r</m>, <em>scales</em> the length of the vector by a factor of <m>
			r</m> and flips its direction if <m>r \lt 0</m>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-plot-mult-vectors">
			<caption>A plot showing multiplication of vectors</caption>
			<image width="75%" xml:id="plot-mult-vectors">
				<latex-image>
				<![CDATA[
				\begin{tikzpicture}
				\draw [->] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
				\draw [->] (0,-3) -- (0,3);
				\foreach \x in {-2,-1,1,2} {\draw (\x,-0.1) -- (\x,0.1) node [at start, below] {$ \x$};}
				\foreach \y in {-2,-1,1,2} {\draw (-0.1,\y) -- (0.1,\y) node [at start, left] {$ \y$};}
				\draw [->,very thick] (0,0) -- (2,1) node [above] {$ \boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw [->,very thick] (0,-1) -- (4,1) node [right] {$ 2\boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw [->,very thick] (0,2) -- (-2,1) node [left] {$ -\boldsymbol{v}$};
				\end{tikzpicture}
				]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
	</subsection>

	<subsection>
		<title>Vector Addition</title>
		<p>
			As we saw in the previous chapter, vector addition in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> is
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				\boldsymbol{u} + \boldsymbol{v} = \begin{bmatrix}
				u_1 \\ u_2
				\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix}
				v_1 \\ v_2
				\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
				u_1 + v_1 \\ u_2 + v_2
				\end{bmatrix}
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Consider two vectors <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> in the plane:
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-plot-two-vectors">
			<caption>A plot of two vectors in the plane</caption>
			<image width="50%" xml:id="plot-two-vectors">
				<latex-image>
				<![CDATA[
				\begin{tikzpicture}
				\draw[->,very thick] (0,0) -- (2,1) node [midway, below right] {$ \boldsymbol{u}$};
				\draw[->,very thick] (-2,1) -- (-1,4) node [midway, above left] {$ \boldsymbol{v}$};
				\end{tikzpicture}
				]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
			The sum of these vectors can be represented by taking the <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> vector, then drawing
			the <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> at the tail end of the <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> vector.
			The resulting vector
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-plot-sum-vectors">
			<caption></caption>
			<image width="50%" xml:id="plot-sum-vectors">
				<latex-image>
				<![CDATA[
				\begin{tikzpicture}
				\draw[->,very thick] (0,0) -- (2,1) node [midway, below right] {$ \boldsymbol{u}$};
				\draw[->,very thick] (2,1) -- (3,5)node [midway, below right] {$ \boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw[->,very thick] (0,0) -- (3,5) node [pos=0.75, above left] {$ \boldsymbol{u}+\boldsymbol{v}$};
				\end{tikzpicture}
				]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
			starts at the beginning of <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and ends at the end of <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> as seen
			above.
		</p>

		<p>
			Another way to think about this is to use <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> as the sides of
			the parallelogram.
			The vector <m>\boldsymbol{u}+\boldsymbol{v}</m> is diagonal from the starting point of
			both <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> extending to the ending point of both.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-plot-vector-parallelogram">
			<caption>The sum of two vectors are the sides of a paralellogram</caption>
			<image width="30%" xml:id="plot-vector-parallelogram">
				<latex-image>
				<![CDATA[
				\begin{tikzpicture}
				\draw[->,very thick] (0,0) -- (2,1) node [midway, below right] {$ \boldsymbol{u}$};
				\draw[->,very thick] (2,1) -- (3,5)node [midway, below right] {$ \boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw[->,very thick] (1,4) -- (3,5) node [midway, above left] {$ \boldsymbol{u}$};
				\draw[->,very thick] (0,0) -- (1,4)node [midway, above left] {$ \boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw[->,very thick] (0,0) -- (3,5) node [midway, above] {$ \boldsymbol{u}+\boldsymbol{v}$};
				\end{tikzpicture}
				]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
	</subsection>

	<subsection>
		<title>Geometry of Addition and Scalar Multiplication in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></title>
		<p>
			As we saw in the previous section, we know how to add and scalar multiply vectors in <m>
			\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
			The geometry of these operations are similar to that in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
			For example, in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>, a vector connects two points in 3-dimensional space.
			Scalar multiplication results in scaling that vector by a factor of <m>r</m>.
			Addition works
			the same way: make the ending point of the first vector, the starting point of the second
			vector.
			The result is the vector from the starting point of the first vector to the ending
			point of the 2nd vector.
		</p>

		<p>
			And this extends to any dimension, <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
			Although this is difficult to
			visualize, it still works the same way.
			Typically there is no need to draw any vectors in
			dimensions above 3.
		</p>
	</subsection>

	<subsection>
		<title>Lines in Vector form in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> and <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m></title>
		<p>
			First, let's look at a line in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> and for example, passes through <m>(2,1)</m>
			and <m>(3,4)</m> and denote the line <m>L</m>.
			This would look like:
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-plot-line-in-r2">
			<caption>A vector version of a line in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m></caption>
			<image width="50%" xml:id="plot-line-in-r2">
				<latex-image>
				<![CDATA[
				\begin{tikzpicture}
				\draw [->] (-4,0) -- (4,0);
				\draw [->] (0,-4) -- (0,4);
				\foreach \x in {-3,-2,-1,1,2,3} {\draw (\x,-0.1) -- (\x,0.1) node [at start, below] {$ \x$};}
				\foreach \y in {-3,-2,-1,1,2,3} {\draw (-0.1,\y) -- (0.1,\y) node [at start, left] {$ \y$};}
				\fill (2,1) circle (2.5pt);
				\fill (3,4) circle (2.5pt);
				\draw[<->] ({1/3},-4) -- ({10/3},5) node [pos=0.8,below right]{$ L$};
				\draw[->,very thick] (2,1) -- (3,4) node [at end, below right] {$ \boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw[->,very thick] (0,0) -- (2,1) node [midway, above] {$ \boldsymbol{u}$};
				\draw[->,very thick, red] (2,1) -- (2.5,2.5) node [midway, below right] {$ t\boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw[->,very thick, red] (0,0) -- (2.5,2.5) node [pos=0.6, above left]  {$ \boldsymbol{u}+t\boldsymbol{v}$};
				\end{tikzpicture}
				]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
			Let's make the vector <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> the vector between the points <m>(2,1)</m> and <m>(3,4)</m>
			as shown on the figure above.
			Recall that a vector and a point is synonymous if the vector
			starts at the origin.
			Call <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> the vector from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(2,1)</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			Next, any point on the line can be written as a vector by addition of <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and a
			scale of <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> or <m>\boldsymbol{u}+t\boldsymbol{v}</m>.
			Thus the line between these two points can
			be written as
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				\left\{
				\begin{bmatrix}
				x \\ y
				\end{bmatrix} =
				\begin{bmatrix}
				2 \\ 1
				\end{bmatrix} + t
				\begin{bmatrix}
				1 \\ 3
				\end{bmatrix} \; | \; t \in \mathbb{R} \right\}
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			This notion extend easily to <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
			The set of points
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				\left\{
				\begin{bmatrix}
				2 \\ 1 \\ 3
				\end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix}
				1 \\ 0 \\ 2
				\end{bmatrix} \; | \; t \in \mathbb{R} \right\}
			</me>
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-plot-line-in-r3">
			<caption></caption>
			<image width="50%" xml:id="plot-line-in-r3">
				<latex-image>
				<![CDATA[
				\tdplotsetmaincoords{70}{130}
				\begin{tikzpicture}[tdplot_main_coords]
				%draw the main coordinate system axes
				\draw[thick,->] (0,0,0) -- (4,0,0) node[anchor=north east]{$ x$};
				\draw[thick,->] (0,0,0) -- (0,4,0) node[anchor=north west]{$ y$};
				\draw[thick,->] (0,0,0) -- (0,0,4) node[anchor=south]{$ z$};
				\draw[-stealth] (0,0,0) -- (2,1,3) node [midway,above left] {$ \boldsymbol{u}$};
				\draw[-stealth,thick] (2,1,3) -- (4,1,1) node [midway,above left] {$ t\boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw[<->] (0,1,5) -- (5,1,0);
				\end{tikzpicture}
				]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="sect-planes-r3">
		<title>Planes in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m></title>
		<p>
			A plane in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> can also be written using vectors although perhaps harder to
			visualize.
		</p>

		<definition>
			<title>Plane</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					A <term>plane</term> in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> is the set of points
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						\{ \boldsymbol{p} + \boldsymbol{u} t + \boldsymbol{v} s \; | t,s \in \mathbb{R} \}
					</me>
				</p>

				<p>
					for nonzero vectors <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{p},\boldsymbol{u}</m> and <m>
					\boldsymbol{v}</m> are vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			Consider the following example in which a parallelogram is drawn in the plane.
			The point <m>
			(2,3,1)</m> in one corner of the parallelogram and the two sides are
		</p>

		<p>
			<md>
				<mrow>
				\boldsymbol{v} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}
				1 \\ 1 \\1
				\end{bmatrix} \amp \boldsymbol{w} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}
				2 \\ 0 \\ -1
				\end{bmatrix}
				</mrow>
			</md>
		</p>

		<p>
			The parallelogram in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> would look like:
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-plot-parallelogram-in-r3">
			<caption></caption>
			<image width="50%" xml:id="plot-parallelogram-in-r3">
				<latex-image>
				<![CDATA[
				\tdplotsetmaincoords{70}{130}
				\begin{tikzpicture}[tdplot_main_coords]
				%draw the main coordinate system axes
				\draw[thick,->] (0,0,0) -- (4,0,0) node[anchor=north east]{$ x$};
				\draw[thick,->] (0,0,0) -- (0,4,0) node[anchor=north west]{$ y$};
				\draw[thick,->] (0,0,0) -- (0,0,4) node[anchor=south]{$ z$};
				\draw[-stealth] (2,3,1) -- (1,1,1) node [midway,above right] {$ \boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw[-stealth] (2,3,1) -- (4,3,0) node [midway,above left] {$ \boldsymbol{w}$};
				\draw[-stealth] (1,1,1) -- (3,1,0) -- (4,3,0);
				\end{tikzpicture}
				]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
			The set of all points on the plane can then be written as
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				\left\{ \begin{bmatrix}
				2 \\ 3 \\ 1
				\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix}
				1 \\ 1 \\ 1
				\end{bmatrix} t +
				\begin{bmatrix}
				2 \\ 0 \\ -1
				\end{bmatrix} s \; | \; t,s \in \mathbb{R} \right\}
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Extending this idea to linear surfaces in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is a natural generalization of
			planes.
		</p>

		<definition>
			<statement>
				<p>
					A <term><m>k</m>-dimensional linear surface</term> in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is the set:
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						\{ \boldsymbol{p} + t_1 \boldsymbol{v}_1 + t_2 \boldsymbol{v}_2 + \cdots + t_k \boldsymbol{v}_k \; | \; t_1, t_2,
						\ldots, t_k \in \mathbb{R} \}
					</me>
				</p>

				<p>
					If <m>k=n-1</m>, then the surface is called a <term>hyperplane</term>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
	</subsection>

	<subsection>
		<title>Geometry of Linear Systems</title>
		<p>
			You should have noticed the the <m>k</m>-dimensional linear surface above has the same form
			as the solution to the general linear system.
		</p>

		<p>
			<ul>
				<li>
					<p>
						If the linear system has one free variable, the solution is a line.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<p>
						If the linear system has two free variables, the solution is a plane (or hyperplane).
					</p>
				</li>
			</ul>
		</p>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="sect-length-angles">
		<title>Length and Angle Measures</title>
		<p>
			Two of the basic ideas of geometry are the notions of length and angles.
			These are
			well-defined in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> and with a relatively easy extension to <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>
			and in this section we generalize to <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
			We'll start with the notion of
			distance as the length of a vector.
			Consider first a vector
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				\boldsymbol{v} = \begin{bmatrix}
				v_1 \\ v_2
				\end{bmatrix}
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			in the plane (<m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>).
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-plot-vector-with-coords">
			<caption>A vector starting at the origin showing the relationship to the
			coordinate sides.
			</caption>

			<image width="50%" xml:id="plot-vector-with-coords">
				<latex-image>
				<![CDATA[
				\begin{tikzpicture}
				\draw [->] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
				\draw [->] (0,-3) -- (0,3);
				%\foreach \x in {-2,-1,1,2} {\draw (\x,-0.1) -- (\x,0.1) node [at start, below] {$ \x$};}
				%\foreach \y in {-2,-1,1,2} {\draw (-0.1,\y) -- (0.1,\y) node [at start, left] {$ \y$};}
				\draw [->,very thick] (0,0) -- (2,1) node [above] {$ \boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw (2,0.1) -- (2,-0.1) node [below] {$ v_1$};
				\draw (0.1,1) -- (-0.1,1) node [left] {$ v_2$};
				\draw (2,0) -- (2,1) node [midway, right] {$ v_2$};
				%\draw [->,very thick] (0,-1) -- (4,1) node [right] {$ 2\boldsymbol{v}$};
				%\draw [->,very thick] (0,2) -- (-2,1) node [left] {$ -\boldsymbol{v}$};
				\end{tikzpicture}
				]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
			and using plane geometry, the length of <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m>, denoted <m>||\boldsymbol{v}||</m> is the
			hypotenuse of the triangle or
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				||\boldsymbol{v}|| = \sqrt{v_1^2+v_2^2}
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			and if <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> is in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>, the length would include a square of the
			third component inside the square root.
			Thus, we defined the length of any vector in <m>
			\mathbb{R}^n</m> to be the following.
		</p>

		<definition>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The <term>length</term> of a vector <m>\boldsymbol{v} \in \mathbb{R}^n</m> is given by
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						|| \boldsymbol{v}|| = \sqrt{v_1^2 + v_2^2 + \cdots v_n^2 }
					</me>
				</p>

				<p>
					which fits our expectations in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> and <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<example>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the length of the vector:
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						\boldsymbol{v} = \begin{bmatrix}
						3 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ -5
						\end{bmatrix}
					</me>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					<me>
						||\boldsymbol{v}|| = \sqrt{9+1+0+25} = \sqrt{35}
					</me>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="sect-angles-of-vectors">
		<title>Angles of vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m></title>
		<p>
			Consider first 2 vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
			The angle between
			them would be the angle (measured in the counterclockwise direction)
			between the vectors if the starting point is anchored at the same place.
			For example:
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-plot-angle-between-vector">
			<caption></caption>
			<image width="50%" xml:id="plot-angle-between-vector">
				<latex-image>
				<![CDATA[
				\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
				\draw [->] (-3,0) -- (4,0);
				\draw [->] (0,-3) -- (0,4);
				\foreach \x in {-2,-1,1,2,3} {\draw (\x,-0.1) -- (\x,0.1) node [at start, below] {$ \x$};}
				\foreach \y in {-2,-1,1,2,3} {\draw (-0.1,\y) -- (0.1,\y) node [at start, left] {$ \y$};}
				\draw[->] (0,0) -- (3,1) node [below right] {$ \boldsymbol{u}$};
				\draw[->] (0,0) -- (-1,2) node [below left] {$ \boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw(9.48pt,3.16pt) arc [radius=10pt, start angle=18.43, end angle=116.56505118] ;
				\draw(0.1,0.3) node [above right] {$ \theta$};
				\end{tikzpicture}
				]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
			where
			<md>
				<mrow>\boldsymbol{u} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}
				3 \\ 1
				\end{bmatrix}, \amp \boldsymbol{v} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}
				-1 \\ 2
				\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
			</md>
			You can find the angle using knowledge of geometry.
			In this case,
			you can make a triangle by connecting the end points of each vector.
			Note that the third leg of the triangle can be written as
			<me>
				\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{u} = \begin{bmatrix}
				-1 \\ 2
				\end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix}
				3 \\ 1
				\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
				-4 \\ 1
				\end{bmatrix}
			</me>
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-plot-vector-diff">
			<caption></caption>
			<image width="40%" xml:id="plot-vector-diff">
				<latex-image>
				<![CDATA[
				\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
				\draw [->] (-1.5,0) -- (4,0);
				\draw [->] (0,-1.5) -- (0,4);
				\foreach \x in {-1,1,2,3} {\draw (\x,-0.1) -- (\x,0.1) node [at start, below] {$ \x$};}
				\foreach \y in {-1,1,2,3} {\draw (-0.1,\y) -- (0.1,\y) node [at start, left] {$ \y$};}
				\draw[->] (0,0) -- (3,1) node [midway, below right] {$ \boldsymbol{u}$};
				\draw[->] (0,0) -- (-1,2) node [midway, below left] {$ \boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw[->] (3,1) -- (-1,2) node [midway, above] {$ \boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{u}$};
				\draw (9.48pt,3.16pt) arc [radius=10pt, start angle=18.43, end angle=116.56505118] ;
				\draw(0.1,0.3) node [above right] {$ \theta$};
				\end{tikzpicture}
				]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
			and the lengths of the three sides are:
			<md>
				<mrow>||\boldsymbol{u}|| \amp = \sqrt{10}, \amp ||\boldsymbol{v}|| \amp= \sqrt{5}, \amp ||\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{u}|| \amp = \sqrt{17} </mrow>
			</md>
			and then using the law of cosines:
			<md>
				<mrow>||\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{u}||^2 \amp = ||\boldsymbol{u}||^2 + || \boldsymbol{v}||^2 -2 ||\boldsymbol{u}|| \,  ||\boldsymbol{v}| \cos \theta \\
				17 \amp = 10+5 - 2 \sqrt{10}\sqrt{5} \cos \theta \\
				\frac{2}{-2 \sqrt{10}\sqrt{5}} \amp = \cos \theta
				</mrow>
			</md>
			which in this case <m>\theta \approx 98.13^{\circ}</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			Note: since the range of <m>\cos^{-1} \theta</m> is <m>[0,\pi]</m>
			(or <m>[0,180^{\circ}]</m>), the angle will always be the angle between
			the vectors with this range.
			If you need the proper angle, you may need
			to subtract the result from <m>360^{\circ}</m>.
		</p>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="sect-angles-vectors">
		<title>Angles of vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></title>
		<p>
			Understanding the above section allows us to extend the notion of
			vectors in <m>n</m> dimensions, with the key being the law of cosines:
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				||\boldsymbol{u}-\boldsymbol{v}||^2 = ||\boldsymbol{u}||^2 + || \boldsymbol{v}||^2 -2 ||\boldsymbol{u}|| \,  ||\boldsymbol{v}| \cos \theta \\
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			and if we expand this out for
		</p>

		<p>
			<md>
				<mrow>\boldsymbol{u} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}
				u_1 \\ u_2 \\ \vdots \\ u_n
				\end{bmatrix} \amp
				\boldsymbol{v} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}
				v_1 \\ v_2 \\ \vdots \\ v_n
				\end{bmatrix}
				</mrow>
			</md>
		</p>

		<p>
			Then,
		</p>

		<p>
			<md>
				<mrow>||\boldsymbol{u}-\boldsymbol{v}||^2 \amp = (u_1-v_1)^2 + (u_2-v_2)^2 + \cdots + (u_n -v_n)^2, </mrow>
				<mrow>||\boldsymbol{u}||^2 \amp = u_1^2 + u_2^2 + \cdots + u_n^2, </mrow>
				<mrow>||\boldsymbol{v}||^2 \amp = v_1^2 + v_2^2 + \cdots + v_n^2,</mrow>
			</md>
		</p>

		<p>
			Expanding the top equation and subtracting the two below:
		</p>

		<p>
			<md>
				<mrow>||\boldsymbol{u}-\boldsymbol{v}||^2-||\boldsymbol{u}||^2-||\boldsymbol{v}||^2  \amp = -2u_1v_1 - 2u_2v_2 - \cdots -2u_nv_n</mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = -2 (u_1 v_1 + u_2 v_2 + \cdots + u_n v_n) </mrow>
			</md>
		</p>

		<p>
			The term in the parentheses appears often throughout linear algebra and is called the <term>dot product</term>
		</p>

		<definition>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The <term>dot product</term> (or <term>inner product</term>) of the
					vectors <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> is defined as
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v}  = u_1v_1 + u_2v_2 + \cdots +u_nv_n
					</me>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			Note:  the dot product between two vectors results in a number (a scalar).
			Also, the dot product is only defined between two vectors of the same length.
			Also, for any vector <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m>, there is a nice relationship between the
			length and the dot product:
		</p>

		<p>
			<me>
				\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{u}   = ||\boldsymbol{u}||^2
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Again, returning to law of cosines and solving for <m>\cos \theta</m>:
		</p>

		<p>
			<md>
				<mrow>\cos \theta \amp = \frac{||\boldsymbol{u}-\boldsymbol{v}||^2-||\boldsymbol{u}||^2-||\boldsymbol{v}||^2}{-2 ||\boldsymbol{u}|| \, ||\boldsymbol{v}||}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = \frac{-2 \boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v}}{-2 ||\boldsymbol{u}|| \, ||\boldsymbol{v}||} </mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = \frac{\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v}}{||\boldsymbol{u}|| \, ||\boldsymbol{v}||}</mrow>
			</md>
		</p>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="sect-dot-prod-props">
		<title>Properties of The Dot Product</title>
		<p>
			As we will see, the dot product is an extremely important concept.
			Before going on, we show the properties of the dot product.
		</p>

		<p>
			<dl>
			<li>
				<title>Commutative</title>
				<p>
					<m>\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v} = \boldsymbol{v} \cdot \boldsymbol{u}</m>,
				</p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Distributative</title>
				<p>
					<m>\boldsymbol{u} \cdot (\boldsymbol{v} + \boldsymbol{w}) = \boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v} + \boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{w}</m>.
				</p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Associative</title>
				<p>
					<m>\boldsymbol{u} \cdot (r\boldsymbol{v}) = (r \boldsymbol{u}) \cdot \boldsymbol{v} = r (\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v})</m>.
				</p>
			</li>
			</dl>
		</p>

		<p>
			These properties can be shown using the Definition above.
		</p>

		<theorem>
			<title>The Triangle Inequality</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					For any <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> both in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, then
				</p>

				<p>
					<men  xml:id="eq-tri-inequal">
						||\boldsymbol{u}+\boldsymbol{v}||   \leq ||\boldsymbol{u}||+||\boldsymbol{v}||
					</men>
				</p>

				<p>
					Equality is only reached if one of the vectors is a nonnegative scalar multiple of the other.
				</p>
			</statement>


			<proof>
				<p>
					First, note that if either <m>\boldsymbol{u} = \boldsymbol{0}</m> or <m>\boldsymbol{v} = \boldsymbol{0}</m>, then
					then <xref ref="eq-tri-inequal" /> holds.
				</p>

				<p>
					Therefore, assume that neither <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> nor <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> is the zero vector.
					Then create
					the vector
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						||\boldsymbol{u}|| \boldsymbol{v} - ||\boldsymbol{v}||\boldsymbol{u}.
					</me>
				</p>

				<p>
					The square of the length of this is nonnegative.
				</p>

				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow>0  \leq \amp ||(||\boldsymbol{u}|| \boldsymbol{v} - ||\boldsymbol{v}||\boldsymbol{u})||^2 </mrow>
						<mrow>\amp = (||\boldsymbol{u}|| \boldsymbol{v} - ||\boldsymbol{v}||\boldsymbol{u}) \cdot (||\boldsymbol{u}|| \boldsymbol{v} - ||\boldsymbol{v}||\boldsymbol{u})</mrow>
						<mrow>\amp  = (||\boldsymbol{u} || \boldsymbol{v}) \cdot (||\boldsymbol{u}|| \boldsymbol{v}) - (||\boldsymbol{u}|| \boldsymbol{v}) \cdot (||\boldsymbol{v}|| \boldsymbol{u})
						- (||\boldsymbol{v} || \boldsymbol{u}) \cdot (||\boldsymbol{u}|| \boldsymbol{v}) + (||\boldsymbol{v}|| \boldsymbol{u}) \cdot (||\boldsymbol{v}|| \boldsymbol{u})</mrow>
						<mrow>\amp \qquad \qquad\text{using properties of the dot product}</mrow>
						<mrow>\amp = ||\boldsymbol{u}||^2 (\boldsymbol{v} \cdot \boldsymbol{v}) - 2 (||\boldsymbol{u}||\boldsymbol{v}  \cdot ||\boldsymbol{v}|| \boldsymbol{u})
						+ ||\boldsymbol{v}||^2 (\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{u})
						</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = \leq ||\boldsymbol{u}||^2 ||\boldsymbol{v}||^2 - 2 ||\boldsymbol{u}|| \, ||\boldsymbol{v}||  (\boldsymbol{v}  \cdot \boldsymbol{u})
						+ ||\boldsymbol{v}||^2 ||\boldsymbol{v}||^2
						</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = \qquad \qquad \text{divide through by $||\boldsymbol{u}|| \, ||\boldsymbol{v}||$} </mrow>
						<mrow xml:id="eq-tri-inequal2" number="yes"> \amp \leq 2||\boldsymbol{u}|| \, ||\boldsymbol{v}|| - 2 (\boldsymbol{v}  \cdot \boldsymbol{u}) </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					Adding <m>||\boldsymbol{u} + \boldsymbol{v}||^2 = (\boldsymbol{u}+\boldsymbol{v}) \cdot (\boldsymbol{u}+\boldsymbol{v})</m> to both sides
				</p>

				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow>
						||\boldsymbol{u} +\boldsymbol{v}||^2 \amp \leq  (\boldsymbol{u}+\boldsymbol{v}) \cdot (\boldsymbol{u}+\boldsymbol{v}) +
						2||\boldsymbol{u}|| ||\boldsymbol{v}|| - 2 (\boldsymbol{v}  \cdot \boldsymbol{u}) </mrow>
						<mrow>
						\amp = \boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{u} + 2 \boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v} + \boldsymbol{v} \cdot \boldsymbol{v} +
						2||\boldsymbol{u}|| ||\boldsymbol{v}|| - 2 (\boldsymbol{v}  \cdot \boldsymbol{u}) </mrow>
						<mrow>
						\amp  = ||\boldsymbol{u}||^2 + 2 ||\boldsymbol{u}||\,||\boldsymbol{v}|| + ||\boldsymbol{v}||^2
						</mrow>
						<mrow>
						\amp  = (||\boldsymbol{u}|| + ||\boldsymbol{v}||)^2
						</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					and lastly, taking the square root of both sides
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						||\boldsymbol{u} + \boldsymbol{v}|| \leq ||\boldsymbol{u}|| + ||\boldsymbol{v}||
					</me>
				</p>

				<p>
					To show equality, assume that <m>||\boldsymbol{v}|| \neq 0</m>,
				</p>

				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow>||\boldsymbol{u}||\boldsymbol{v} - ||\boldsymbol{v}|| \boldsymbol{u} \amp = 0 </mrow>
						<mrow> \text{or} \qquad \qquad \amp </mrow>
						<mrow>\boldsymbol{u} \amp = \frac{||\boldsymbol{u}||}{||\boldsymbol{v}||} \boldsymbol{v}</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					therefore <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> is a scalar multiple of <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m>.
				</p>
			</proof>
		</theorem>

		<p>
			This can be visualized by considering the plane in which <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m>
			and <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> lie (and note that regardless of the value of <m>n</m>,
			they will lie in a plane or planar subset of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.)
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-plot-triangle-inequality">
			<caption>A plot showing the triangle inequality for vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m></caption>
			<image width="50%" xml:id="plot-triangle-inequality">
				<latex-image>
				<![CDATA[
				\begin{tikzpicture}
				\draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (3,1) node [midway,below right] {$\boldsymbol{u}$};
				\draw[->,thick] (3,1) -- (5,3) node [midway,below right] {$\boldsymbol{v}$};
				\draw[->,thick] (0,0) -- (5,3) node [midway,above left] {$\boldsymbol{u}+\boldsymbol{v}$};
				\end{tikzpicture}
				]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
			The vector <m>\boldsymbol{u}+\boldsymbol{v}</m> is one side of the triangle and
			we know that any one side must always be no larger than the sum of
			the other two.
		</p>

		<corollary>
			<title>Cauchy-Swartz Inequality</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> be vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
					Then
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						| \boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v}| \leq ||\boldsymbol{u}|| \, ||\boldsymbol{v}||
					</me>
				</p>

				<p>
					with equality if and only if <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> are scalar multiples of each other.
				</p>
			</statement>


			<proof>
				<p>
					A consequence of the Triangle Inequality is <xref ref="eq-tri-inequal2" />,
					thus the Cauchy-Swartz Inequality holds if <m>\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v} \gt 0</m>.
					Assume that <m>\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v}  \lt 0</m>.
					Then
				</p>

				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow>\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v} = - (\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v}) = (-\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v}) \amp \leq ||-\boldsymbol{u}|| ||\boldsymbol{v}|| </mrow>
						<mrow>
						\text{and since} \; ||-\boldsymbol{u}|| = ||\boldsymbol{u}|| \qquad \amp </mrow>
						<mrow>\amp = ||\boldsymbol{u}|| \, ||\boldsymbol{v}||</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					For equality, assume that <m>\boldsymbol{u} = k \boldsymbol{v}</m> for some real number <m>k</m>.
					Then
				</p>

				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow> |\boldsymbol{u}\cdot \boldsymbol{v} | \amp = |k \boldsymbol{v} \cdot \boldsymbol{v}| </mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = |k| \; |\boldsymbol{v} \cdot \boldsymbol{v} | </mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = |k| \; || \boldsymbol{v} ||^2 </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					and since these steps are reversible, this hold for if and only if.
				</p>
			</proof>
		</corollary>

		<p>
			We now use the dot product to define the angle between two vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
		</p>

		<definition>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The <term>angle between vectors</term> <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> is the value of <m>\theta</m> that satisfies:
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						\cos \theta = \frac{ \boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v}}{||\boldsymbol{u}||\, ||\boldsymbol{v}||}
					</me>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			So now with any two vectors, the above expression is a way to define the angle between them.
		</p>

		<example>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the angle between
				</p>

				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow>\boldsymbol{u} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}
						2 \\ -4 \\ 1 \\ 1
						\end{bmatrix} \amp \boldsymbol{v} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}
						3 \\ 2 \\ 0 \\ 5
						\end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow>||\boldsymbol{u}|| \amp =\sqrt{22}, \amp ||\boldsymbol{v}|| \amp = \sqrt{38} </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						\boldsymbol{u} \cdot \boldsymbol{v} = 6-8+0+5 = 3
					</me>
				</p>

				<p>
					and therefore the angle can be found by
				</p>

				<p>
					<me>
						\cos \theta = \frac{3}{\sqrt{22}\sqrt{38}} \approx 0.1037571696
					</me>
				</p>

				<p>
					and <m>\theta \approx 84.04^{\circ}</m>.
					And although it's difficult to
					visualize these vectors, we can imagine the angle between them.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<p>
			One of the most important angles in geometry is <m>\theta=90^{\circ}</m>,
			which occurs in right triangles and perpendicular lines.
			In terms
			of vectors, we use the dot product to define this.
		</p>

		<definition>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Two vectors <m>\boldsymbol{u}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m> are <term>perpendicular</term>
					or <term>orthogonal</term> if their dot product is 0.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
	</subsection>
</section>